Author-Workplace-Name: Ewha Women's University 
Author-Name: Michael S. Rozeff 
Title: Long-run Performance after Stock Splits: 1927 to 1996 
Abstract:
 We measure the postsplit performance of 12,747 stock splits from 1927 to
 1996 using two methods to measure abnormal returns: size and
 book-to-market reference portfolios with bootstrapping, and calendar-time
 abnormal returns combined with factor models. Between 1927 and 1996,
 neither method applied to splits 25 percent or larger finds performance
 significantly different from zero. Over selected subperiods, subsamples of
 2-1 splits restricted by book-to-market availability requirements display
 positive abnormal returns using some methods. However, these samples show
 small or negligible abnormal returns using the calendar-time method.
 Overall, the stock split evidence against market efficiency is neither
 pervasive nor compelling. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
